            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1562333519,
            "creation_date": 1562333519,
            "body": "<p>If I understood your problem well, you have 2 lists of strings, <code>A<\/code> and <code>B<\/code>. The goal is to determine which strings in <code>B<\/code> are a prefix of a string in <code>A<\/code>.<br>\nThen, there exists a data structure, called <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trie\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">trie<\/a>, which does exactly that.<br>\nFirst, you need to insert each string of <code>A<\/code> into your trie.<br>\nThen for each string of <code>B<\/code>, you can do the following: traverse the trie by reading the current string (or word). If you cannot go till the end of the word because a node is missing, then the current word is not the 'child' of any object'.<br>\nOn the other hand, if you finish the current word and are still on the trie, then you word is a prefix of a word stored beforehand.\nYou should find implementations of java tries (or ideas on how to implement them) <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/java+trie\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 56904085,
            "question_id": 56903441
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/LREX2.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 2168743,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1921273,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1921273/mrsmith42",
                "reputation": 10181,
                "display_name": "MrSmith42"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1562337956,
            "creation_date": 1562335204,
            "body": "<p>Depending on the length of your names you could create a map of all prefixes of the child-names in the first pass. (Costs <strong>O(n*nameLength)<\/strong> time) <\/p>\n\n<p>Than you can lookup for each parent in <strong>O(1)<\/strong> (if you use a <em>HashMap<\/em>) which children have the parents-name as prefix.<\/p>\n\n<p>You should definitely try to avoid <em>RegExp<\/em> for matching. these are not cheap! <\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>P.s.\nYou could also google for \"prefix-trees\", if it's only about detecting prefixes.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 56904520,
